do you ever feel like you don’t deserve to eat?

let me tell ya…

there’s a whole lot more where that came from.

licking my plate: “no macro left behind” - I would actually feel anxious if I didn’t lick my plate and get every last gram of food because my macros wouldn’t be perfect. I was also so hungry I didn’t want to waste a bit of food I was allotted.

eating out of the trash: when I was in a binge mindset or had an “intuitive day” or a “free meal” I would go to the grocery store and get everything I wanted, bring it back home and binge binge binge. I’d get to a point where I was “done” and threw the rest away… a few minutes later I’d go grab it out of the trash and eat it because it’s all I could think about.

sleep binging: I think this was probably the craziest out of body experience of them all? I’d wake up in the middle of the night, go to the kitchen and eat everything. mostly protein bars (that I tried to hide from myself lol) and peanut butter because those are the two things I’d keep in the house that were “fear foods.” my body was so hungry, it would get up in the middle of the night and eat

I couldn’t imaging doing these things now and I never thought I’d be able to say that. all of these naturally disappeared when I healed my relationship with food and became an intuitive eater.

If you do these too, instead of being embarrassed, understand your body is trying to tell you something isn’t quite right. lack of food (mentally or physically) can make you do some crazy things. give yourself grace

The other day I was in Aritzia and come to find out their dressing rooms don’t have mirrors…

You have to go out into the “common area” to use the same mirror as everyone else trying on clothes.

I had a mini panic attack and tried to prop my phone camera up to look at my outfit so I didn’t have to go out there.

It didn’t work and ultimately I sucked it up and had to use the common mirror with everyone else.

I’m not someone who gets triggered much anymore, but I was thrown through a loop here… NOT AN OUNCE OF ME EXPECTED TO WALK INTO A DRESSING ROOM WITHOUT MIRRORS???

(@aritzia , if you’re reading this my entire community and I would love to petition for mirrors in each individual dressing room. ps. love you)

I immediately started comparing myself to the tiny girls who looked absolutely gorgeous in their new clothes.

I needed larger sizes in everything and they were all asking for smaller sizes.

Not to mention I didn’t have a bra which made everything ten times more awkward lol

Anyway, I posted about this on stories when it happened and one of you DMed me asking how I got through this moment of being triggered and wishing I was smaller like the other girls.

These are the top 3 things I kept repeated to myself:
1. Just because they’re small, doesn’t mean they’re healthy or living their best life. They could very well struggle with food, exercise and even have bad body image too. You never know what someone is going through and you can’t tell based on their body size. If I were any smaller, I wouldn’t be able to live my best life.

2. I need food anyway. I was starting to get hungry and even though I was triggered and had a moment of wishing I was smaller, I ate anyway.

3. There’s no reason for me to be jealous or envious of them because they are in a smaller body, my body size isn’t mine to control and neither is theirs. If they do control their body size, that’s their choice but I know that doesn’t give me the life I desire to live.

You can’t control what challenges you’re faced with but you CAN control you how you react.

Has someone ever complimented your weight loss but they were actually complimenting one of these?

Weight loss isn’t always a good thing, weight gain isn’t a bad thing.

Weight gain may actually be the healthiest thing you can do.

There are so many other things about you that are worthy of a compliment - your personality, how you make others feel, the impact you have on others, the work you do.

These comments can make you afraid to heal, to get better, out of fear of weight gain, judgement from others and lack of validation.

You’re more than your body and I’m sorry if anyone has ever made you feel like that’s all you are.

Can we normalize consistently eating enough, instead of eating as little as possible?

Not eating all day isn’t a flex, it’s actually a big reason you feel out of control around food at night, once you finally eat.

Your body NEEDS “a lot” of food every single day

This week I challenge you do give it just that

Example below👇🏼

My breakfast the other day: plain oats w/ flax, cinnamon, date syrup & whole milk, berries and almond butter (not weighed/measured/tracked in any way) + eggs on the side.

I got about 3/4 of the way through my oats and couldn’t eat anymore.

I became uninterested
It didn’t sound or taste good anymore
My tummy felt full and satisfied

I knew this from learning my fullness cues which I wasn’t able to learn until I fully learned, honored and satisfied my hunger cues.

So I honored my fullness, put the bowl in the fridge and finished it later when I got hungry again (or sometimes I’ll let honey finish it😉)

At this point, I’m usually pretty good at eyeballing how much food it’ll take to satisfy my hunger and *usually* end up being close to spot on and finishing my plate.

But sometimes by body tells me it’s too much so I save it for leftovers or toss it

Or sometimes I need a little more so I go back for seconds (last night I went back three times for more lemon bars from TJs and ended up being satisfied after four) and that’s okay!

But, how much I eat isn’t based on numbers in any way, it’s based on feelings.

The problem isn’t that you don’t know enough…

It’s that you know too much

It’s caused you to obsess, overanalyze, and second guess every decision you make about food

You don’t need to have the nutrition label of every food memorized… you actually don’t really need to pay attention to them

You don’t need to know every calorie you consume… you actually don’t need to count calories at all

& you absolutely don’t need to know the serving sizes grams of macros by heart… or at all

It’s possible to unlearn all of this and make eating easy again.

When you diet, every week or sometimes even every day you see visible progress. But it doesn’t last long, eventually your diet fails you. You fall off track, you gain all the weight back and you feel even worse about yourself. Fleeting feelings of self confidence.

Then you restart another diet, or start tracking macros again, and the cycle repeats.

Yea intuitive eating is hard. Healing your relationship with food sucks at times, especially at the beginning. But it won’t always suck. You’re getting down to the root problem and solving it rather than slapping a bandaid on it with another diet or “lifestyle change.”

But it’ll be messy until you unlearn and relearn everything you know about fitness and nutrition.

Delayed gratification.

Story time👇🏼

I had an interesting relationship with food for years before I found tracking macros. being a female athlete growing up (gymnastics), I was destined for some disordered behaviors—literally no way around it…

I found tracking and thought this was the answer to getting the body I wanted while having freedom around food.

Then things got worse when I started bodybuilding even thought felt like I had total control over food—in reality FOOD WAS CONTROLLING ME.

After I turned pro, all hell broke loose and I couldn’t muster up the willpower to sick to my macros any longer.

I hit rock bottom and I knew I had to make a change. I couldn’t continue living like this. I couldn’t continue thinking about food 24/7, obsessing over my body, and planning my day around my workouts.

Healing my relationship with food and learning to become an intuitive eater was the only way out.

Now none of these things are part of my life in any way and it feels so liberating. These things never gave me control, they took the power away from me.

Even though it’s scary to let go of the control—it’s not scary forever. Your worst fears aren’t going to come true and there’s nothing scarier than living the rest of your life being a slave to myfitnesspal, your food scale, and weighing yourself.

As someone who’s on the other side and has guided many women to food freedom, I can say it’s absolutely possible for you to honor your value of living a healthy lifestyle without planning all your meals, weighing all your food, and thinking about how your body looks 24/7—so you can be present in the moment and enjoy your life while prioritizing your health.

#foodfreedom #intuitiveeating #macrocounting #caloriecounting

here’s why👇🏼 (briefly)

1️⃣counting calories or macros: its totally unnecessary to live a healthy lifestyle and have healthy habits. For many, it causes more harm than good and totally takes the joy out of life—call me dramatic haha.

2️⃣“good” or “bad” foods: food doesn’t have moral value, food is literally just food. eating a specific food shouldn’t make you feel like you are “good” or “bad.” all food serves a purpose.

3️⃣intermittent fasting: ignoring your body when it tells you to eat sets you up for eating past fullness when you finally allow yourself to eat. food is energy and we need consistent energy to get us through the day.

4️⃣ozempic for weight loss: uh, ozempic should be used for the purpose it was intended for. using it for anything but is abuse. I have so many thoughts, maybe another post…

5️⃣bmi: you can’t determine the health of an individual based on one single number, you also can’t base health on body size or weight because that’s not a behavior. bmi was never intended to measure individuals. completely flawed and complete bs.

Do any surprise you? Would love to hear your thoughts!
